data <- read.csv("DATA/regression data sheet_sydney.csv")


data_sydney <- data %>%
  filter(City == "Sydney ")%>% 
  group_by(City, Distance, habitat, site, type, name, individual) %>% 
  summarise(mean_herbivory = mean(herbivory, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'City', 'Distance', 'habitat', 'site',
## 'type', 'name'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
data_newcastle <- data %>%
  filter(City == "Newcastle")

Overall herbivory model

overall_model <- glmmTMB(mean_herbivory ~ Distance + (1|site) + (1|name/ individual), family = tweedie, data = data_sydney)
overall_intercept <- fixef(overall_model) [[1]]["(Intercept)"]
overall_slope <- fixef(overall_model)[[1]] ["Distance"]
summary(overall_model) #slope is on log scale as well as the intercept
##  Family: tweedie  ( log )
## Formula:          
## mean_herbivory ~ Distance + (1 | site) + (1 | name/individual)
## Data: data_sydney
## 
##      AIC      BIC   logLik deviance df.resid 
##   8753.6   8792.6  -4369.8   8739.6     1949 
## 
## Random effects:

sim1 = simulateResiduals(overall_model)

plot(sim1)

#creating a custom regression line using the length of the predictor variable and the regression slope of the dependent variable
distance_herbivory <- seq(from = 0, to = 30, length.out = 10000) 
predict_herbivory <- exp(overall_intercept + overall_slope*distance_herbivory) #we put exp because the herbivory data is log transformed from the above model, this means that we dont log something twice when we make the graph
emmeans_herbivory <- data.frame(emmeans(overall_model, ~ Distance, at = list(Distance = distance_herbivory), type = "response"))#exponentiates the model predictions
view(emmeans_herbivory)

species_plot <- data_sydney %>%
group_by(Distance,name) %>% 
summarise(mean_mean_herbivory = mean(log1p(mean_herbivory)))

## `.groups` argument.
overall_plot <- ggplot(species_plot, aes(Distance, exp(mean_mean_herbivory))) +

How does herbivory change depending on the site it is found

habitat_data <- data_sydney %>% 
  filter(name %in% c("Modiola caroliniana", "Plantago lanceolata", "Taraxacum officinale", "Commelina cyanea", "Dichondra repens", "Hypochaeris radicata", "Bidens pilosa", "Conyza canadensis", "Glycine tabacina"))

habitat_model<- glmmTMB(mean_herbivory ~ 1 + Distance*habitat + (1|site) + (1|name/ individual), family = tweedie, data = data_sydney)
summary(habitat_model)
